(850, 'Edwardtoipt', 'joanbush1920@salpingomyu.ru', 'US candy prices have climbed in the past year kra26 at', 'Escazu Chocolates, a bean-to-bar chocolate shop in Raleigh, North Carolina, sources most of its beans from Latin America. The shop said it has always worked with smaller farmers and paid them three to four times the commodity price of cacao â which essentially sets the minimum wage. The spike in prices has pushed up what Escazu pays those workers as well. \r\n<a href=https://kra39at.cc>kra20</a> \r\nOther cost-cutting measures include offering a smaller hot chocolate size, advertising non-chocolate ice cream toppings and moving to a cheaper location in Raleigh to save on rent. \r\n<a href=https://kra39-cc.net>kra25 at</a> \r\nAnd like many small businesses in America, Escazu is being hit by President Donald Trumpâs tariffs, affecting not just the chocolate, but also aluminum in its packaging. \r\n<a href=https://kra9.net>https kra39 cc</a> \r\nâThe tariffs have hit every single piece of what goes into every single thing,â Tiana Young, co-owner of Escazu, told CNN. âThere is no new normal.â \r\nhttps kra39 at \r\nhttps://kpa37.cc', '2025-11-10 10:32:30.251586'),
(851, 'RufusunakE', 'marierykaczewski1928@salpingomyu.ru', 'Trump says heâs ordered Pentagon to âprepare kra1', 'Cheung, who regularly expresses hostility toward reporters on social media platform X, asserted in a Friday night post that, âsome reporters have been caughtâ taking pictures of sensitive information and âeavesdropping on private, closed-door meetings.â \r\n<a href=https://kra-34cc.ru>httpkra39cc</a> \r\nThat claim came as news to White House press corps leaders, who are not aware of colleagues being âcaught.â \r\n<a href=https://kra41-cc.net>kra11</a> \r\nEarly in Bill Clintonâs presidency, Clinton aides similarly attempted to bar journalists from the âupper pressâ area, causing an outcry. That ban was rescinded. \r\n<a href=https://kra-42-at.net>kraken16.at</a> \r\nJournalists had normal access to the offices during President Trumpâs first term in office. But in his second term, Trump and his aides have taken several steps to stymie news coverage and circumvent traditional media outlets. \r\n<a href=https://kra---45--at.ru>kra9</a> \r\nLast winter, the administration blocked the Associated Press from attending some White House events, leading to a First Amendment lawsuit that is still working its way through the courts. \r\n<a href=https://kra--40---cc.ru>??????????????????????</a> \r\nThe administration has also stopped publishing transcripts of Trumpâs remarks; has taken control of daily press pool assignments; and has invited fawning pro-Trump commentators to presidential Q&As. \r\n<a href=https://kra44---at.ru>kra30??</a> \r\nSome cabinet secretaries have followed Trumpâs lead. Last month, Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth implemented severe new restrictions for Pentagon press pass credentialing, leading virtually every major media outlet to reject the rules and give up access to the Pentagon complex. \r\n \r\nCNNâs Samantha Waldenberg contributed to this report. \r\n??????????????????????????? \r\nhttps://kra-42-cc.net', '2025-11-10 10:34:29.370803'),
(852, 'HectorLug', 'ritadavis1984@salpingomyu.ru', 'Trump administration restricts ??????????? ???? ?????? ??????', 'Members of the White House press corps are now restricted from the press secretaryâs office, the latest in a series of Trump administration actions to limit media access. \r\n<a href=https://kra49-at.net>http kra40 cc</a> \r\nThe new rule says journalists cannot access whatâs known as the âUpper Pressâ office space, where White House press secretary Karoline Leavitt works, âwithout an appointment.â \r\n \r\nThis area has been accessible to White House correspondents for decades, supporting a free flow of information between the president and the public. \r\n<a href=https://kra--45.cc>kra41 ??</a> \r\nThe White House says the clampdown is due to security concerns. \r\n \r\nâThis policy will ensure adherence to best practices pertaining to access to sensitive material,â a White House memo asserted on Friday night. \r\n<a href=https://kra-44.cc>?????? ???? ??????</a> \r\nIn response, the White House Correspondentsâ Association, which represents hundreds of credentialed reporters, said it âunequivocally opposes any effortâ to limit journalists from areas that have long been accessible for newsgathering, âincluding the press secretaryâs office.â \r\n \r\nâThe new restrictions hinder the press corpsâ ability to question officials, ensure transparency, and hold the government accountable, to the detriment of the American public,â the association said. \r\n<a href=https://kra41cc.com>kra41 at</a> \r\nAs CNNâs Jeff Zeleny explained, reporters routinely âwait in the hallâ by the press secretaryâs office and seek information from communications aides. âWhen there is breaking news, that often happens,â Zeleny said. \r\n \r\nNow, âreporters will only have access to a smaller set of offices of junior advisers, junior aides, junior press secretaries,â according to the White House. \r\nkra45 at \r\nhttps://at-kra45.cc', '2025-11-10 10:41:19.856860'),
