(1721, 'Joanna Riggs', 'joannariggs278@gmail.com', 'Video Promotion for your website?', 'Hi,\r\n\r\nI just visited uromijdpci.org and wondered if you\'ve ever considered an impactful video to advertise your business? Our videos can generate impressive results on both your website and across social media.\r\n\r\nOur videos cost just $195 (USD) for a 30 second video ($239 for 60 seconds) and include a full script, voice-over and video.\r\n\r\nI can show you some previous videos we\'ve done if you want me to send some over. Let me know if you\'re interested in seeing samples of our previous work.\r\n\r\nRegards,\r\nJoanna', '2026-06-15 07:03:36.415190');
INSERT INTO `Events_newsletter` (`id`, `title`, `brief`, `volume`, `number`, `edition`, `date`, `slug`, `image`, `newsletter`) VALUES
(1, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER, MARCH 2024', 'INTRODUCTION \r\nUromi JDPCI is passionately committed to promoting justice and peace, fostering meaningful development, and providing support to the less privileged. Our dedication is reflected in the wide array of initiatives we undertake, all aimed at advancing comprehensive human development through inclusive and engaging programmes that unite key stakeholders. In the Human Rights Education and Paralegal Scheme, Uromi JDPCI conducted quarterly learning sessions with adolescent human rights clubs in 26 secondary schools across five Local Government Areas (LGAs). We also organized quarterly meetings with paralegals and human rights advocates in 30 communities within the Edo Central Senatorial District. A closeout ceremony and stakeholders conference on inclusive human rights defense highlighted our commitment to this cause. Through the Migration and Countering Trafficking in Persons (CTIP) desk, Uromi JDPCI has executed numerous activities to reduce human trafficking in Edo State. These efforts included extensive anti-human trafficking campaigns in 10 secondary schools and 10 communities, forming child champion clubs in schools, and establishing child protection groups in communities. We conducted sensitization meetings with transporters, mapped and engaged influential actors, trained mentors and social protection officers, and developed advocacy strategies and self-protection manuals for community child champions and school clubs. In our Galvanize Action for Effective Trafficking In Persons Response Project, Uromi JDPCI organized community sensitization and public awareness rallies for the International Day of Prayer and Awareness Against Human Trafficking. We held advocacy meetings with State government officials and cluster coaching sessions to enhance local capacity in trafficking response. Through the Integrated Child Health and Social Services Award, Uromi JDPCI facilitated community HIV testing, medication pickup, viral load sampling, and enhanced adherence counseling. We also organized Operation Triple Zero (OTZ) and gender norm sessions for adolescents living with HIV/AIDS, empowered female students, and supported caregivers through various programs. Our micro-credit scheme provided soft loans to small and medium-scale enterprises and active farmers within the five LGAs of the Edo Central Senatorial District, resulting in numerous success stories. Under the Correctional Center Apostolate, Uromi JDPCI conducted spiritual and counseling services for inmates and presented food items at the Ubiaja Correctional Center on behalf of the Bishop of Uromi Diocese, Most Rev. Dr. Donatus Ogun OSA. In our Environment and Climate Change intervention, we raised awareness on waste management and tree planting. Finally, Uromi JDPCI conducted sensitization campaigns in parishes to strengthen JDPC activities at the parish level, promoting justice, development, and peaceful co-existence within the parishes and the broader community', 31, 39, 'VOL. 31 NO. 39, MARCH 2024', '2024-11-05', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-march-2024', 'newsletter-images/Screenshot_from_2024-11-06_12-00-05.png', 'newsletters/MARCH_2024_pAs0sZP.pdf'),
(2, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER DECEMBER 2023 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nAligned with the Uromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI) mission to contribute to a society where people coexist in peace,Uromi JDPCI implemented various interventions during this period. These activities were in harmony with the mission of promoting integral human development through the motivation and participatory actions involving relevant stakeholders. The goal was to advocate for policy reforms, empower individuals, and enhance human dignity for a more meaningful existence. In the Human Rights Education and Paralegal Scheme project, Uromi JDPCI conducted quarterly learning sessions with adolescent human rights clubs in 26 secondary schools across the 5 Local Government Areas (LGAs) in Edo Central Senatorial District. Quarterly meetings with Paralegals and Human Rights Advocates were also organized with the representatives of 30 communities within the Edo Central Senatorial District. Additionally, Uromi JDPCI commemorated the 2023 16 Days of Activism Against Gender-Based Violence and the 2023 World Human Rights Day. Within the Migration and Countering Trafficking in Persons (CTIP) desk, Uromi JDPCI engaged in advocacy visits with relevant stakeholders, held a Project Inception Meeting, and mapped out target communities and schools for the implementation of the AACTING project. In the same vein, Uromi JDPCI conducted activities such as M P Social Dialogue and Interfaith Forums, Advocacy Engagement Meetings with the Chairman of Esan North East Local Government Area, Cluster coaching sessions, Learning Sessions, and Trainingsunder the Galvanize Action for Effective Trafficking in Persons Response project. Through its Integrated Child Health and Social Services Award, Uromi JDPCI facilitated HIV testing, screening, and the pickup of ART drugs, along with Enhanced Adherence Counselling (EAC). The Uromi JDPCI also organized Operation Triple Zero (OTZ) club sessions and gender norm sessions for Adolescents Living with HIV/AIDS. Bi-monthly review meetings with Community/Facility Case Managers were part of the initiatives. Furthermore, Uromi JDPCI observed the 2023 World AIDS Day. Uromi JDPCI sustained its micro-credit empowerment scheme by providing soft loans to Small and Medium Scale enterprises and active farmers within the 5 Local Government Areas of the Edo Central Senatorial District to boost their businesses and farms. Under the Correctional Center Apostolate, Uromi JDPCI celebrated Christmas Party with Inmates in Ubiaja Correctional Center. Finally, the organization conducted sensitization campaigns in parishes to reinforce JDPC activities at the parish levels. The aim was to foster collaboration in promoting justice, meaningful development, and peaceful co-existence, both within the parishes and the broader community', 30, 38, 'VOL. 30 NO. 38 DECEMBER 2023', '2024-11-06', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-december-2023-edition', 'newsletter-images/1.jpg', 'newsletters/NEWSLETTER_DECEMBER_2023_PK3YCOS.pdf'),
(3, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER, SEPTEMBER EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI) sustained her efforts at contributing to a just and developed society where people coexist in peace by the series of interventions carried out within this period. These activities were in line with her mission to promote integral human development through motivation and participatory actions with relevant stakeholders toward policy reforms, empowerment of the people, and enhancement of human dignity for meaningful living. In the Human Rights Education and Paralegal scheme project, Uromi JDPCI conducted quarterly learning sessions with school-based adolescent human rights clubs in 26 Secondary Schools across the 5 LGAs, quarterly meeting with Paralegals and Human Rights Advocates in 30 communities across the 5 LGAs in Edo Central Senatorial District, and sensitization on gender equality across the 5 LGAs. In the migration and Countering Trafficking in Person (CTIP) desk, Uromi JDPC Imade advocacy engagement meetings with stakeholders. Quarterly Cluster coaching and learning session were also conducted in the Galvanize Action for Effective Trafficking in Persons Response project. Uromi JDPCI through her Integrated Child M P Health and Social Services Award facilitated HIV testing and screening, ART drug pick up and Enhanced Adherence Counselling (EAC), Operation Triple Zero (OTZ) club sessions for Adolescents Living with HIV/AIDS, andbi monthly review meeting sessions with Community/Facility Case Managers. Uromi JDPCI also sustained her micro credit empowerment Scheme by providing soft loans to Small and Medium Scale enterprises and active farmers within the 5 Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District to enhance their businesses. Under the Correctional Center Apostolate, Uromi JDPCI conducted group and individual Spiritual/Legal Counsellings for Inmates at the Ubiaja Correctional Center. On Environment and Climate Change, Uromi JDPCI expanded the drive to plant fruit trees and flowers in the Chancery compound and St. Theresa Catholic Church compound Ukoni. Lastly, Sensitizations were carried out in Parishes to strengthen JDPC activities at the Parish levels with a view to collaborate in promoting justice, meaningful development and peaceful co existence both at the Parishes and the larger community', 29, 37, 'VOL.  27 NO. 37 SEPTEMBER 2023 EDITION', '2024-11-06', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-september-edition', 'newsletter-images/1_OEf4X9P.jpg', 'newsletters/SEPTEMBER_2023_EDITION_12g32lZ.pdf'),
(4, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 32 N0. 40 JUNE 2024 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION \r\nUromi JDPCI is deeply committed to the promotion U of justice and peace, the fostering of meaningful development, and the provision of support to the vulnerable members of the society. Our diverse initiatives reflect this dedication, as we strive to advance comprehensive human development through inclusive and engaging programmes that unite key stakeholders. In our Human Rights Education and Paralegal Scheme, we commemorated the international day against Child labour and abuse. We conducted quarterly learning sessions with adolescent human rights clubs across 26 secondary schools in five Local Government Areas (LGAs) in Edo Central Senatorial District and also organized quarterly meetings with paralegals and human rights advocates in 30 communities within the Edo Central Senatorial District, culminating in a robust discussion and experience sharing. Through our Migration and Countering Trafficking in Persons (CTIP) desk, we executed a variety of activities aimed at reducing human trafficking in Edo State. These efforts included facilitation of child protection committee meetings in 10 communities, quarterly learning sessions with Child Champions both at the school and community levels and biannual caregivers/parent forum. We also had an engagement meeting with the Edo State Taskforce against Human Trafficking. In collaboration with the Integrated Child Health and Social Services Award, our initiatives included Operation Triple Zero (OTZ) and gender norm sessions for adolescents living with HIV/AIDS, alongside programmes designed to empower female students and support caregivers. Our micro-credit scheme has provided soft loans to small and medium-scale enterprises and active farmers across the five LGAs of the Edo Central Senatorial District, resulting in numerous success stories. Under the Correctional Center Apostolate, we offered spiritual and counseling services for inmates at the Ubiaja Correctional Center. In our Environment and Climate Change intervention, we commemorated the International Mother Earth Day and World Environment Day. These were used to raise awareness on tree planting initiatives as part of climate change mitigation strategies. Finally, Uromi JDPCI conducted sensitization campaigns in parishes to strengthen JDPC activities at the parish level, promoting justice, development, and peaceful coexistence within the parishes and the broader community.', 32, 40, 'VOL. 32 NO. 40 JUNE 2024', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-32-n0-40-june-2024-edition', 'newsletter-images/1_VFBazZd.jpg', 'newsletters/JUNE_2024_CORRECTED.pdf'),
(5, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 29 N0. 37 SEPTEMBER 2023 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI) sustained her efforts at contributing to a just and developed society where people coexist in peace by the series of interventions carried out within this period. These activities were in line with her mission to promote integral human development through motivation and participatory actions with relevant stakeholders toward policy reforms, empowerment of the people, and enhancement of human dignity for meaningful living. In the Human Rights Education and Paralegal scheme project, Uromi JDPCI conducted quarterly learning sessions with school-based adolescent human rights clubs in 26 Secondary Schools across the 5 LGAs, quarterly meeting with Paralegals and Human Rights Advocates in 30 communities across the 5 LGAs in Edo Central Senatorial District, and sensitization on gender equality across the 5 LGAs. In the migration and Countering Trafficking in Person (CTIP) desk, Uromi JDPC Imade advocacy engagement meetings with stakeholders. Quarterly Cluster coaching and learning session were also conducted in the Galvanize Action for Effective Trafficking in Persons Response project. Uromi JDPCI through her Integrated Child M P Health and Social Services Award facilitated HIV testing and screening, ART drug pick up and Enhanced Adherence Counselling (EAC), Operation Triple Zero (OTZ) club sessions for Adolescents Living with HIV/AIDS, andbi monthly review meeting sessions with Community/Facility Case Managers. Uromi JDPCI also sustained her micro credit empowerment Scheme by providing soft loans to Small and Medium Scale enterprises and active farmers within the 5 Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District to enhance their businesses. Under the Correctional Center Apostolate, Uromi JDPCI conducted group and individual Spiritual/Legal Counsellings for Inmates at the Ubiaja Correctional Center. On Environment and Climate Change, Uromi JDPCI expanded the drive to plant fruit trees and flowers in the Chancery compound and St. Theresa Catholic Church compound Ukoni. Lastly, Sensitizations were carried out in Parishes to strengthen JDPC activities at the Parish levels with a view to collaborate in promoting justice, meaningful development and peaceful co existence both at the Parishes and the larger community.', 29, 37, 'VOL. 29 NO. 37 SEPTEMBER 2023', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-29-n0-37-september-2023-edition', 'newsletter-images/1_ZTjijss.jpg', 'newsletters/SEPTEMBER_2023_EDITION_juLFUvT.pdf'),
(6, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 10 NO. 18 DECEMBER 2018 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nThe efforts of Uromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI) in promoting good governance through community engagement, creating awareness on the dangers of human trafficking and irregular migration as well as ensure meaningful living for the people of Esan Land continued to yield successes in the various intervention conducted in this quarter. In the good governance desk, Uromi JDPCI conducted five quarterly meetings across the five Local Government Areas in Edo Central Senatorial District. The plans of the various groups to participate in the forth coming election took the center stage of discussion with members suggesting diverse ways of preventing vote buying and money politics. Uromi JDPCI also conveyed a senatorial eminent stakeholderâs forum which was attended by traditional rulers and political representatives across Esan land Uromi JDPCI also conducted advocacies visits and awareness creation to communities, schools, churches and government institutions with the aim to sensitize them on the ills of human trafficking and irregular migration. As a way of creating alternative for households in the prevention of human trafficking Uromi JDPCI empowered 75 students and 75 caregivers with five thousand for school materials and eighty five thousand naira grant for business respectively. The micro credit desk also attracted a lot of clients most of whom signified interest in the Agricultural empowerment. The petty traders were also empowered to sustain their businesses and improve their livelihood. With Micro credit support to rural and semi urban farmers as well as petty traders, Uromi JDPCI is creating livelihood opportunity and promoting economic empowerment. Uromi JDPCI was also at the prison to celebrate the Christmas season with the inmates as well as collaborated with other persons to do the same.', 10, 18, 'VOL. 10 NO. 18 DECEMBER 2018', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-10-no-18-december-2018-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall.jpg', 'newsletters/26_NEWSLETTER_FOR_DECEMBER_2018.pdf'),
(7, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 25 NO. 33 SEPT. 2022 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI) through her wide-ranging streams of interventions promotes the integral development of the rural populace in Edo Central Senatorial District in accordance with her mission, which is to alleviate poverty and promote integral development through the motivation and empowerment of the less privileged/oppressed and challenging unjust structures that enhance injustice, hatred and backwardness in Nigeria. These interventions address challenges and norms around human rights protection, good governance, human trafficking and Irregular Migration, as well as interventions to promote healthy outcomes amongst children and families infected and affected by HIV/AIDS. In her Human Rights Education and Paralegal scheme project, Uromi JDPCI conducted series of activities geared towards improving peaceful coexistence in the communities. Among which were Community Dialogue in 5 Communities, the facilitation of Adolescent Human Right Club Learning Sessions in 25 schools, the sensitization of representatives of 30 communities on Gender issues and Gender-based violence, training of paralegals and human rights advocates, and the conveyance of third Quarterly Meeting of Paralegals. Uromi JDPCI also implemented some activities in collaboration with communities to strengthen good governance and encouraged community participation in governance for effective service delivery. The activities were: town hall meetings/media engagement, quarterly learning sessions, and monitoring visits to target communities. In the anti-human trafficking desk, Uromi JDPCI trained and empowered 40 caregivers across communities in Edo Central Senatorial District. Five tertiary education students were also supported with grants for tuition fees. These were part of the Donât Pay With Your Life Projectâs effort to reduce susceptibility to human trafficking. Uromi JDPCI through the GATIP project also conducted some advocacy engagement meetings geared towards localizing trafficking in-person response at the LGAs in Edo State. Some public awareness events such as a rally to mark world day against human trafficking and the launching of campaign hashtags were also conducted Uromi JDPCI through her Integrated Child Health and Social Service Award facilitated Operation Triple Zero (OTZ) Club Meetings for Adolescents Living With HIV/AIDS at Uromi Central Hospital and Irrua Specialist Teaching Hospital, the project also conducted community outreach for HTS as well as followed up on clients with unsuppressed viral load record. Uromi JDPCI also sustained her micro-credit empowerment Scheme by providing soft loans to Small and Medium Scale enterprises and active farmers within the 5 Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District to enhance their businesses.', 25, 33, 'VOL. 25 NO. 33 SEPTEMBER 2022', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-25-no-33-sept-2022-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_1.jpg', 'newsletters/2022_Q3_UROMI_JDPCI_NEWSLETTER_JULY-SEPTEMBER_UPDATED_MWbdO4z.pdf'),
(8, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 26 NO. 34 DECEMBER EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI) through her wide-ranging streams of interventions geared toward contributing to a just and developed society where people coexist in peace conducted several activities in accordance with her mission, which is to promote integral human development through motivation and participatory actions with relevant stakeholders towards policy reforms, empowerment of the people and enhancement of human dignity for meaningful living. These activities were spread across varied projects and interventions being implemented by Uromi JDPCI. In the Human Rights Education and Paralegal scheme project, the following activities were conducted: quarterly learning sessions with school-based adolescent human rights clubs in 25 Secondary Schools across the 5 LGAs, quarterly meeting with Paralegals and Human Rights Advocates in 30 communities across the 5 LGAs in Edo Central Senatorial District, community dialogues with stakeholders in 4 communities, and the commemoration of World Human Right Day. In the migration and Countering Trafficking in Person (CTIP) desk, Uromi JDPCI implemented some activities across two projects, which were; the Donât Pay with Your Life (DPWYL) and the Galvanize Action for Effective Trafficking in Persons Response at the LGA Level in Edo State (GATIP). In the DPWYL project, the following activities were conducted: entry advocacy visits to the LGAs, Focus Group discussions with social protection officers, group discussions with caregivers, group discussions with young female returnees, and monitoring visits to adolescents enrolled in vocational skills acquisition. While the GATIP project implemented the following activities: training on understanding and embedding human trafficking and unsafe migration response in Nigeria, training on budget analysis and monitoring processes, cluster coaching, and learning session. Uromi JDPCI through her Integrated Child Health and Social Service Award facilitated HIV testing and Screening, Operation Triple Zero (OTZ) Club Meetings for Adolescents Living With HIV/AIDS at Uromi Central Hospital and Irrua Specialist Teaching Hospital, Caregivers forum, 16 days of activism against gender-based violence, gender norms training in 10 secondary schools and review meetings with community case managers and Facility managers. Uromi JDPCI also sustained her micro-credit empowerment Scheme by providing soft loans to Small and Medium Scale enterprises and active farmers within the 5 Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District to enhance their businesses. Uromi JDPCI also paid an annual Christmas visit to the inmates in Ubiaja Correctional Center to celebrate the Christmas season with them.', 26, 34, 'VOL. 26 NO. 34 DECEMBER 2022', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-26-no-34-december-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_2.jpg', 'newsletters/2022_Q4_UROMI_JDPCI_NEWSLETTER_NEW_MKhQwua.pdf'),
(9, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 24 NO. 32 JUNE 2022 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (uromi JDPCI) through her wide-ranging streams of interventions promotes integral development of the rural populace in Edo Central Senatorial District in accordance with her mission, which is to alleviate poverty and promote integral development through the motivation and empowerment of the less privileged/oppressed and challenging unjust structures that enhance injustice, hatred and backwardness in Nigeria. These interventions address challenges and norms around human rights protection, good governance, human trafficking and Irregular Migration, as well as interventions to promote healthy outcomes amongst children and families infected and affected by HIV/AIDS. Therefore, in attainment of one of her goal, which is to contribute towards improving peaceful coexistence of the village communities and promoting social justice and respect for human rights under her Human Rights Education and Paralegal Scheme Project, Uromi JDPCI facilitated Community Dialogue in Four Communities and Adolescent Human Right Club Learning Sessions all in Edo Central Senatorial District. The International Day of Child Protection was commemorated and execution of the Second Quarterly Meeting (April-June, 2022) of the Human Right Clubs. Relentlessly working to end the ills of Human Trafficking and Irregular Migration in Edo Central Senatorial District, Uromi JDPCI under her Strengthening Capacity to Prevent Human Trafficking Project conducted 2 community and 1 market sensitization to enlighten community dwellers on the dangers associated with Human Trafficking and Irregular Migration. Also, sessions were held with Anti-human trafficking clubs across 10 secondary schools in Edo Central Senatorial District while Community Dialogue meetings were held in four Communities. Uromi JDPCI through her Donât Pay With Your Life Project facilitated monitoring visits to 50 caregivers and 14 young female Returnees supported by the project in Income Generating Activities to improve their livelihood conditions and reduce their vulnerability to human trafficking. From the visits it was discovered that 41 caregivers and 9 returnees were able to sustain their businesses. The caregivers were also able to sustain the beneficiaries (adolescent girl child) in secondary school with 33 of them successfully graduating from secondary school and one in tertiary institution. Galvanize Action for Effective Trafficking in Persons Response at the Local Government Level in Edo State. This intervention was birthed due to the need to activate and institutionalize trafficking in persons response at the LGAs of Edo State and has since inception on Monday the 31st of May 2022 carried out strategic advocacy engagement meeting with 4 (Four) Critical Stakeholders and also paid advocacy entry visits to Critical Stakeholders in Etsako West Local Government Area. Uromi JDPCI through her Integrated Child Health and Social Service Award facilitated Operation Triple Zero (OTZ) Club Meetings for Adolescents Living With HIV/AIDS at Uromi Central Hospital and Irrua Specialist Teaching Hospital, formed eight Village Savings and Loan Associations, held two review meetings with community and facility case managers and also convened Cluster-Level Meeting with National Population Commission to strengthen collaboration with NPopC to facilitate birth registration for OVC enrolled in the ICHSSA 2 Project and also provide mentorship on the completion of the live birth registration form known as Form B1. State Level Meeting with State Universal Basic Education Board (SUBEB) was also facilitated to strengthen collaboration with schools in the Local Government Areas (LGAs) within the scope of ICHSSA 2 Project implementation of the project. Uromi JDPCI also sustained her micro credit empowerment Scheme by providing soft loans to Small and Medium Scale enterprises and active farmers within the 5 Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District to enhance their businesses.', 24, 32, 'VOL. 24 NO. 32 JUNE 2022', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-24-no-32-june-2022-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_f1kztTO.jpg', 'newsletters/2022_UROMI_JDPCI_NEWSLETTER_APRIL-JUNE_ZVtoFFl.pdf'),
(10, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 14 NO. 22 DECEMBER 2019 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives sustained developmental effort across its thematic areas to contribute to peaceful coexistence, better information sharing and improved livelihood in the five Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District. In the human rights desk, Uromi JDPCI sustained efforts at capacity building for Human Rights Club members and Paralegals in 25 communities. Quarterly meeting was also held to coordinate information and experience sharing. It also serve as a platform for shared learning, development of synergy and mobilization of local resources for effective response to human rights promotion in the selected communities. Uromi JDPCI joined the rest of the world to commemorate the World Human Right Day. The focus was on womenâs rights to inheritance and the cultural practice of widow inheritance: The position of the law. Uromi JDPCI also engaged in sensitization across communities, schools, markets and churches to raise awareness on the danger of human trafficking and irregular migration and promote the need to curb the ugly trend in Edo Central Senatorial District. This led to the engagement of 24 vulnerable young persons into vocational skill acquisition in Esan South East and Esan Central LGAs. 100 caregivers of vulnerable young persons were also supported with grant of Fifty Thousand Naira (NGN50,000) each to start an Income Generating Activity or improve the one that they already had. All these were part of efforts to create alternative to irregular migration for the beneficiaries. Uromi JDPCI also completed the household assessment for another set of fifty household whoâs adolescent girls are in Government secondary school with a bid to improve their livelihood and economic capacity to retain their children in school so as to be less susceptible to human traffickers. In the same vein Uromi JDPCI joined in the revigourated effort to promote environmental protection through the implementation of the Clean Energy Cook Stove Innovation which resulted in the sensitization of community women on the application of rock to their traditional cookstove. In the same vein, Uromi JDPCI provided welfare and spiritual support to the inmates in Ubiaja prison through the celebration of Christmas Carol with the inmates. The Micro Credit desk also sustained the empowerment drive with the provision of support to beneficiaries in groups across communities in Edo Central Senatorial District.', 14, 22, 'VOL. 14 NO. 22 DECEMBER 2019', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-14-no-22-december-2019-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_1_h4GDMlu.jpg', 'newsletters/NEWSLETTER_FOR_DECEMBER_2019.pdf'),
(11, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 8 NO. 16 JUNE 2018 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nThe goal of institutionalizing good governance in this quarter took a reasonable and applaudable dimension with the successful conduct of town hall meetings with the newly elected Local Government Chairmen in Edo central Senatorial District.This meetings were tagged round table discussions because the Chairmen were actually not given stewardship but were receiving inputs from their people and explaining their plan in office to them. This was to create a yardstick to measure their activities and achievements in Office as well as helped the people make inputs into the Local Government budget and participate in the governance of their own affair Uromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives conducted five quarterly meetings across the five Local Government Areas in Edo Central Senatorial District in this quarter. The emphasis was on strengthening the relationship and collaboration between the newly elected Local Government Chairmen and their People through the civic groups. Inputs were also taken on the level of community participation in governance and how they were able to influence project to their various communities. In the course of the meeting the Director Uromi JDPCI gave opening remark in all the Local Government Areas. In his remark he thanked the civic group members for their enthusiastic participation in the round table discussion with the Executive Chairmen of their Local Government Areas and implored them to ensure a follow up on the issues presented as well as to get their Councillors involved in the follow up. He further advised them to take advantage of the platform the council Chairmen have created for the continuous engagement to bring about progress in their respective communities. A dialogue with their councillors was important to constantly remind the Chairman of his promises. He further urged them to be concern about project going on in their communities through monitoring to ensure that the projects meet standard. He noted that transparency, accountability and participatory democracy were important to achieve community development. He further implored them to collaborate with government for every project sited in their communities to ensure durability and strife to sustain it to the advantage of the community.', 8, 16, 'VOL. 8 NO. 16 JUNE 2019', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-8-no-16-june-2018-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_LTFfPUj.jpg', 'newsletters/NEWSLETTER_FOR_JUNE_2018_COMPLETE.pdf'),
(12, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 12 NO. 20 JUNE 2019 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nAs part of her efforts to promote social justice, improve the knowledge of human rights of citizens and a means to devise a more effective Alternative Dispute Resolution system, Uromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiative in partnership with MISEROR Germany, embarked on an advocacy for human rights education and paralegal scheme to help create awareness as well as track human right violations. A target of 27 human rights clubs, 57 paralegals, 250 human rights advocates and 5 supervisors was set and executed and thus far executed in this first quarter. This advocacy visits were made to traditional leaders, institutional leaders, religious leaders, FIDA, NBA, NSCDC, the Nigerian Police Force and the ministry of justice. In a similar line, Uromi JDPCI also intensified efforts to sensitize communities, schools, markets and churches on the need for safe migration while discouraging human trafficking and irregular migration on the platform of sustainable measures against trafficking in persons (SMAT-P). In this respect, contact was made with 1571 made of 716 males and 852 females including children from amongst 1 market, 14 schools and 2 churches in 2 LGAs in Edo Central Senatorial District. In the same vein, Uromi JDPCI provided welfare and spiritual support to the inmates in Ubiaja prison. The first was the provision of food items from the Bishop, another was collaboration with a family to celebrate Easter at the Prison, then the baptism of 26 inmates and procurement of materials for the prison skills acquisition center. The Micro Credit desk sustained the empowerment drive with the provision of support to 76 beneficiaries in 9 groups across communities in Edo Central Senatorial District.', 12, 20, 'VOL. 12 NO. 20 JUNE 2019', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-12-no-20-june-2019-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_Oa6ixfI.jpg', 'newsletters/NEWSLETTER_FOR_JUNE_2019.pdf'),
(13, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 16 NO. 24 JUNE 2020 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives sustained developmental effort across its thematic areas to contribute to peaceful coexistence, better information sharing and improved livelihood in the five Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District. Uromi JDPCI provided another round of capacity building for the Paralegals and human rights advocates in 26 communities across the five LGAs. The training was on Gender Equality and Gender Based Violence. Uromi JDPCI also facilitated quarterly meeting of paralegals to allow for experience sharing and shared learning. This was to strengthen the effort for the development of synergy and mobilization of local resources for effective response to human rights promotion in the selected communities across the five LGAs. Uromi JDPCI also supported forty three beneficiaries in the Donât Pay With Your Life project with One Hundred Thousand Naira each to set up Income Generating Activities. Monitoring visits were also conducted to beneficiaries in previous project while both beneficiaries were engaged in discussion on Childrenâs personality with a bid to improve their capacity for improved caregiving which would reduce susceptibility to human trafficking and irregular migration. Uromi JDPCI further engaged in monitoring visit to beneficiaries of the SMAT-P project with a view to determine achievements of the project which was implemented to curb the ugly trend of human trafficking and irregular migration in Edo Central Senatorial District. The Micro Credit desk also sustained the empowerment drive with the provision of support to beneficiaries in groups across communities in Edo Central Senatorial District. There is great improvement in the assessment of loan through bank transfer. Although the refund of loan is still manual', 16, 24, 'VOL. 16 NO. 24 JUNE 2020', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-16-no-24-june-2020-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_mHOqrKC.jpg', 'newsletters/NEWSLETTER_FOR_JUNE_2020_6mkOe1z.pdf'),
(14, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 15 NO 23 MARCH 2020 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives sustained developmental effort across its thematic areas to contribute to peaceful coexistence, better information sharing and improved livelihood in the five Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District. In the human rights desk, Uromi JDPCI improved the capacity of Human Rights Club members and Paralegals in 27 communities with training on the Legal system, Judicial procedures and basic legal terms, quarterly meeting for experience sharing and shared learning. This was to strengthen the effort for the development of synergy and mobilization of local resources for effective response to human rights promotion in the selected communities across the five LGAs. Uromi JDPCI also conducted monitoring to beneficiaries in previous project as well as engaged some of the beneficiaries across the five LGAs in discussion on better parenting with a bid to improve their capacity for improved caregiving which would reduce susceptibility to human trafficking and irregular migration. Uromi JDPCI also engaged in sensitization across communities, schools and church to raise awareness on the danger of human trafficking and irregular migration and promote the need to curb the ugly trend in Edo Central Senatorial District. Parentsâ-caregiversâ dialogue on human trafficking and irregular movement in three LGAs was also facilitated within this period In the same vein, Uromi JDPCI provided welfare and spiritual support to the inmates in Ubiaja prison through the celebration of New Year with the inmates and the provision of food stuff to them during Easter. The Micro Credit desk also sustained the empowerment drive with the provision of support to beneficiaries in groups across communities in Edo Central Senatorial District. There is great improvement in the assessment of loan through bank transfer. Although the refund of loan is still manual', 15, 23, 'VOL. 15 NO. 23 MARCH 2020', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-15-no-23-march-2020-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_x4lW4vU.jpg', 'newsletters/NEWSLETTER_FOR_MARCH_2020_DNbukT1.pdf'),
(15, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL 9 NO. 17 SEPTEMBER 2018 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nUromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI) sustained her engagement for good governance with the strengthening of the capacities of civic group members across the five Local Government Areas in Edo Central Senatorial District to effective engage their representatives for community growth and development. This was done through quarterly meetings which were held in the month of September, 2018 in all of the five Local Government Areas in Edo Central Senatorial District. The meeting provided opportunity for shared learning and experience sharing among the various civic groups in each of the Local Government Areas. The emphasis in this quarter was on strengthening and developing of improvement plans for the sustainability of the civic group intervention across the target communities. In the course of the meeting the Director Uromi JDPCI gave opening remark in all the Local Government Areas. In his remark he thanked the civic group members for their sustained zeal and commitment since the commencement of the project and then implored them to continue with the same zeal even at the end of the project. He noted that what has been achieved was impressive but would require commitment and dedication to sustain them. He encouraged the groups to be active participants in political activities in their communities as passiveness would not yield the desire results in community development and political engagement. He further urged them to involve the traditional and community leaders in all their engagements. Uromi JDPCI concluded her SMILE intervention in Esan North East Local Government Area with lofty benefit to the households. Some households got cash transfer while some others got improved tree crops, all in an effort to improve their overall well-being. Concerted effort was also made to increase sensitization and campaign against human trafficking in Esan Land through sensitization visits to churches, schools, mosque, motor park and market. Some households were also assessed for empowerment with a bid to reduce their susceptibility to human trafficking. The micro credit department kept the vision of enterprise development alive through support to farmers and petty traders with verifiable enterprise. The prison apostolate desk took the health of the inmates as a priority in this quarter. This was done through health education and HCT.', 9, 17, 'VOL. 9 NO. 17 SEPTEMBER 2018', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-9-no-17-september-2018-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_YQt79QR.jpg', 'newsletters/NEWSLETTER_FOR_SEPTEMBER_2018_2.pdf'),
(16, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 13 NO. 21 SEPTEMBER 2019 EDITION', 'INTRODUCTION\r\nAs part of her efforts to promote social justice, improve the knowledge of human rights of citizens, and a means to devise a more effective Alternative Dispute Resolution system, Uromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiative in partnership with MISEROR Germany embarked on a Human Rights Intervention across 5 Local Government Areas of Edo Central Senatorial District. Thus far executed this quarter include; gender equality sensitization bordering on Female disinheritance and women inclusion in family and societal life, 2nd Quarterly meeting of paralegals, Biannual Conference of Paralegals and Training on Justice Administration and Conflict Management for Paralegals and Human Rights Advocates. As part of efforts to promote collaborative initiatives at strengthening security in Esan Land an eminent stakeholders forum was conveyed to address salient issues for peaceful coexistence in the senatorial district. In a view to retain school adolescent girls in schools so that they do not get lured by human traffickers, Uromi JDPCI carried out activity to select would be beneficiaries of an intervention âDONâT PAY WITH YOUR LIFEâ In a similar line, Uromi JDPCI also intensified efforts to sensitize communities, schools, markets and churches on the need for safe migration while discouraging human trafficking and irregular migration on the platform of sustainable measures against trafficking in persons (SMAT-P). In this respect, contact was made with 699 made of 291 males and 408 females including children from amongst 2 market, 3 schools and 4 communities in 2 LGAs in Edo Central Senatorial District. In the same vein, Uromi JDPCI provided welfare and spiritual support to the inmates in Ubiaja prison through the provision of toiletries and the offering of Holy Mass with a family The Micro Credit desk sustained the empowerment drive with the provision of support to 1062 beneficiaries in 85 groups across communities in Edo Central Senatorial District.', 13, 21, 'VOL. 13 NO. 21 SEPTEMBER 2019', '2024-11-12', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-13-no-21-september-2019-edition', 'newsletter-images/Church_Newsletter_Design_-_Made_with_PosterMyWall_IP7snpK.jpg', 'newsletters/NEWSLETTER_FOR_SEPTEMBER_2019_FINAL_COPY.pdf'),
(18, 'Uromi JDPCI Newsletter vol. 33 No. 41 September 2024 edition', 'Uromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI) sustained engagement with communities and stakeholders across thematic areas to promote social justice and contribute to peaceful coexistence, and sustainable development while supporting the less privileged.', 33, 41, 'vol. 33 No. 41 September 2024', '2025-09-17', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-33-no-41-september-2024-edition', 'newsletter-images/33.jpg', 'newsletters/Uromi_JDPCI_Newsletter_Vol_TWz3eQu._33_No._41_September_2024_Edition.pdf'),
(19, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 34 NO. 42 DECEMBER 2024 EDITION', 'Uromi JDPCI\'s quarterly activities reflect a steadfast commitment to justice, human rights, and community development.', 34, 42, 'DECEMBER 2024', '2025-09-18', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-34-no-42-december-2024-edition', 'newsletter-images/34.jpg', 'newsletters/Uromi_JDPCI_Newsletter_Vol._34_No._42_December_2024_Edition.pdf'),
(20, 'UROMI JDPCI NEWSLETTER VOL. 35 NO. 43 MARCH 2025', 'At Uromi Justice Development Peace and Caritas Initiatives (Uromi JDPCI), the first quarter of 2025\r\nmarked significant progress in advancing our mission to uphold justice, protect the vulnerable, and\r\nempower communities across Edo Central Senatorial District. This edition of our quarterly newsletter highlights our diverse interventions across key thematic areas.', 35, 43, 'MARCH 2025', '2025-09-18', 'uromi-jdpci-newsletter-vol-35-no-43-march-2025', 'newsletter-images/35.jpg', 'newsletters/Uromi_JDPCI_Newsletter_Vol._35_No._43_March_2025_Edition.pdf');
INSERT INTO `Events_program` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `image`, `slug`) VALUES
(1, 'Good governance', 'The essence of governance is to make life more meaningful for the citizens and dwellers in the country. The process of electing leaders into position of authority is through the democratic process. There are several national political parties on whose platforms candidates emerge to campaign for votes. However, there is not so much that is known about the ideologies and programmes of these parties. While the government is making efforts to bring reforms into the electoral process through the newly signed electoral law, and the increased use of technology in the voting process, there is high level of illiteracy among the electorate. Aspiring into elective position costs so much financially. Vote buying is still being witnessed. Uromi JDPCI and other CSOs that are into good governance do organise political engagement programmes that encourage elected political leaders to give account of their stewardship to the electorate. The system requires more of such feedback mechanisms. The political parties also need to educate the electorate on their partiesâ ideologies and the programmes they have to bring about good governance.', 'programs/2150246558.jpg', 'good-governance'),
(2, 'Health', 'There are many health issues that the people of Edo central senatorial district contend with. These include inadequate knowledge about their health, inadequate health facilities (primary and even secondary health facilities), inadequate water to maintain proper personal hygiene and environmental sanitation. Many public schools do not have good toilet facilities. TB and HIV are still spreading, and those suffering from them are still stigmatized. There are many orphans and vulnerable children to cater for with very limited resources. \r\nWomen in many homes require the authorization of their husbands to access medical care. Poverty rate is high and it is a leading cause of people not being able to access good health care. Issues about mental health is becoming significant because people are affected by the poor economic situation, traumatized by the harsh situation and many are losing their minds.\r\nUromi JDPCI, has in the past carried out interventions involving awareness creation on HIV/AIDS, TB screening, escort services, household economic strengthening for infected and affected households among others. It is important to continue with the programmes on health education and public sensitization on health related issues, so that the populace can accord more priority to their health.', 'programs/2149117843_hyXqA9F.jpg', 'health'),
(3, 'Livelihood support', 'A World Bank report (March 2022) stated that sluggish growth, low human capital, labour market weaknesses, and exposure to shocks are holding Nigeriaâs poverty reduction back. As many as 4 in 10 Nigerians live below the national poverty line. Many Nigerians lack access to basic education and infrastructure, such as electricity, safe drinking water, and improved sanitation. Unemployment rate is high. Effects of climate change such as flooding has destroyed homes, farmlands, and roads. Conflicts between farmers and herders are multiplying. Extension services for farmers are near non-existence; and access to farm inputs and farm credits are not readily available. \r\n As a result of high-rate of unemployment, a great number of young people now get themselves engaged in criminal activities. Robbery, kidnapping, vandalisation of oil pipelines and oil bunkering are on the rise. A Get-rich-quick attitude has pervaded the society and people are lured by various Ponzi schemes and lotteries. Prostitution, human trafficking, kidnapping, rape and child abuse cases are on the increase. There is an exodus of Nigerians migrating to foreign countries where many people, including children, have lost their lives in search of greener pastures.\r\nThere is a great need for agro-entrepreneurship knowledge and skill development, and a need to strengthen and improve the various agricultural value chains in order to fully exploit the benefits of the enterprises.', 'programs/2148931120.jpg', 'livelihood-support'),
(4, 'Human rights', 'Many people are not aware of, and cannot defend their fundamental human rights. Most people are not aware of the legal frameworks that exist to safeguard them from being subjected to human rights abuses. Law enforcement agencies often carry out indiscriminate arrest and detention of some young people on the allegation of cybercrime. Pursuing a case in court comes with huge financial cost, not forgetting the unending delays before justice is served. \r\nCertain bad cultural practices, such as ill treatment of widow, levirate marriage, denial of female rights to inheritance constitute violation of the rights of the affected persons. Gender stereotypes exist, spousal battery and other abuses like these are often suppressed under the culture of silence. There is a need to intensify awareness and education on peopleâs rights and obligations, and to support structures and systems that will make it easy for the poor and vulnerable people to seek and obtain justice.', 'programs/2148905520.jpg', 'human-rights'),
(5, 'Migration and countering trafficking in persons', 'Irregular migration and human trafficking especially of youths and children remain a concern in Edo State. The push and pull factors include poverty aggravated by unemployment, a high rate of inflation, and the devaluation of the naira. Many youths due to greed, peer pressure and ignorance of the knowledge of migration protocols are often eager to travel to foreign countries, especially Europe, thus making hasty decisions; preferring to risk irregular migration through the Sahara Desert and the Mediterranean Sea rather than remain in poverty among others.\r\nRecent trends have also shown that traffickers exploit the lack of knowledge of migration protocols to prey on the vulnerability of their victims. They obtain fake travel documents for their victims, aid their travels successfully to Europe and then subject them to various exploitations. Technological  advancement has worsened the situation as traffickers also use social media platforms, posting fake job adverts to lure their victims, especially young people. \r\nUromi JDPCI has over the years made considerable efforts to address these issues through awareness creation campaign, engaging vulnerable households in skill acquisition and economic empowerment to reduce their susceptibility to human traffickers, dialoguing with communities to forge local solutions and way forward in curbing human trafficking and irregular migration and also engaging with the government to create local government response unit to the issue. Efforts have to be intensified by all concerned agencies to step up awareness creation and provide economic alternatives to vulnerable households as traffickers are constantly changing their mode of operations coupled with the increasing inflation and hardship in the country.\r\nSexual and gender-based violence, and child early and forced marriage (SGBV/CEFM)\r\nIncreased poverty has led to rising cases of sexual and gender-based violence and child early and forced marriages in the society. Poverty in the family makes the children vulnerable to abuse, neglect, abandonment or being forced into early marriage by those who are supposed to provide for their needs.  The results of these include rape, teenage pregnancy, and sometimes vesicovaginal fistula (VVF). \r\nEdo state, like most other states is patriarchal by social norms. These norms have encouraged the practice of silence in the midst of spousal abuses, ill treatment of widows, child abuse and neglect, sexual assault, female disinheritance and the likes. What is more, most of the victims are economically dependent, hence are not able to fight for justice. There is no alternative welfare system put in place by government to address the psychosocial, medical and legal needs of survivors. The social works departments in the LGAs saddled with the responsibilities to tackle issues of SGBV and CEFM are not effective. Personnel with the technical knowhow to address the issues through ADR are limited. The cost of litigation is high and the security agents with the onus to collate evidence and transfer cases for prosecution do not do so with transparency, accountability, and due diligence. These factors and more lead to the poor management of cases and few victims of these violations who had the courage to speak up in the face of violation have suffered stigmatization.\r\nUromi JDPCI through previous interventions have set up community structures to address issues around SGBV/ CEFM. These structures include community human rights clubs and adolescent human rights clubs in schools across the Senatorial District and the participants were trained on recognizing SGBV/CEFM cases, how to conduct dialogues and sensitizations in communities of the LGAs. Going forward, there is the need to intensify efforts and deploy new strategies to effectively address the issues around SGBV/ CEFM. These efforts and strategies include the identification of new partners; strengthening the capacity of new and existing partners; training of personnel whose duties cut across serving justice for survivors of SGBV/CEFM, the establishment of co-ordination links where cases are tracked and effectively managed; strategic advocacies; meaningful dialogues; sensitization campaigns using both the mainstream media and social media; as well as strategic empowerment of victims/caregivers of child victims of SGBV/CEFM.', 'programs/2149039147.jpg', 'migration-and-countering-trafficking-in-persons'),
(6, 'Legal & Correctional service apostolate', 'The Police sometimes carry out indiscriminate arrest and detention of suspects. Long investigations and delay in the charging of suspects to courts contribute to overcrowding in police cells and in correctional facilities. The conditions in Nigerian Custodial Centers are in gross violation of the SDGs No. 6: (clean water and sanitation for all) and No.16: (access to justice for all, and effective, accountable, and inclusive institutions at all levels). The Bangkok Rule âprescribes a minimum standard for the treatment of women inmates, but this is not strictly adhered to in Nigeria. Pregnant female inmates who have special needs like ante-natal and post-natal care services and other general medical necessities are often overlooked, and not attended to.\r\nThe present Standing Order of the Nigerian Correctional Service does not allow awaiting trial inmates to participate in rehabilitative engagements. Programming for social development â by state and non-state actors often exclude inmates. Vocational and recreational facilities are either absent or poorly maintained. Civil Society Organisations (FBOs, CBOs, and NGOs) like Uromi JDPCI provide relief materials and medical service outreaches to ameliorate the deplorable conditions in Custodial Centers. Many inmates require medical including psychiatric and psychological support. Many also require legal aid. \r\nProvisions in the ACJL have alternatives to imprisonment, but these are yet to be activated as the mechanisms are not clearly defined. Borstal homes are not adequate; only two are functional in the whole country. And the modalities to operationalize community service are not clear yet. \r\nUromi JDPCI has assisted inmates who do not have legal representation to get legal aid with minor offences. Uromi JDPCI has provided legal aid that has helped to reduce overcrowding and indiscriminate detention that usually leads to poor welfare and inadequate medical attention of inmates with minor offences. The welfare package provided a skill acquisition centre for the inmates and 144 mattresses gifted to the correctional centre. The need to improve spiritual counselling led to the construction of Chapel in the correctional centre at Ubiaja.', 'programs/2148578108.jpg', 'legal-correctional-service-apostolate'),
(7, 'Micro-credit', 'Access to business capital by active-poor people is a big hurdle. They find it difficult to obtain loans from banks, and the interest they have to pay is discouraging. Microcredit services are small loans made available to small producers otherwise known as the active poor to enable them start new productive activities, grow or sustain existing ones. Also, it is a means of extending credit, usually in the form of small loans to members with the group savings as collateral, to non-traditional under-served borrowers. The primary aim is to enhance the wellbeing of the underprivileged through improved access to small loans which are not provided by formal business institutions.  \r\nUromi JDPCI started a micro-credit scheme to assist micro-credit group members to start, expand or sustain their businesses. The scheme has helped many beneficiaries with a high degree of loan recovery. There is the need to invest more funds in the scheme so as to serve many more beneficiaries, and to provide financial literacy and social enterprise development education to those served.', 'programs/2149142889.jpg', 'micro-credit'),
(8, 'Environment and climate change', 'The effect of climate change is now being felt in many ways including the destruction of properties and loss of lives through floods and through natural disasters. Due to deforestation, indiscriminate bush burning, and desert encroachment in the northern part of the country, there is greater pressure on the use of land in the rainforest and savanna belts of the country which often leads to herdsmen-farmers clashes. The ways our natural resources are being exploited expose the people to a lot of health hazards, economic disenfranchisement, and a high level of insecurity in the country. Indiscriminate disposal of waste remains a worrisome issue \r\nThere is a high level of ignorance of the effects of climate change on the environment. Awareness on the use of alternative energy like solar is still low. Waste management is mainly in the hands of private waste collectors who collect, sort (into metals, plastic, and paper) and sell whatever they are able to salvage from the dumpsites. \r\nThere is the need to intensify awareness about climate change, introduce measures that will reduce the emission of carbon-dioxide into the atmosphere, and promote the use of renewable energy as alternatives to fossil fuel. To be able to do these effectively, there is the need to improve the organisational capacity in terms of knowledge, skill, and collaboration with relevant governmental and non-state actors involved in this area of work.', 'programs/2149894697.jpg', 'environment-and-climate-change');
